## Frequently Asked Questions

### Is the Easee One compatible with Intelligent Octopus Go?

No. The Easee One does not support smart tariff integration with Octopus Intelligent Go, Octopus Agile, or similar dynamic tariffs. You can set a manual charging schedule in the app to charge during off-peak hours, but the charger won't automatically optimise for the cheapest slots. If smart tariff support is important to you, the [Ohme Home Pro](/reviews/ohme-home-pro-review/) is the better choice.

### Can I install multiple Easee One chargers at a block of flats?

Yes — this is one of the Easee One's standout features. Up to three units can run from a single 32A fuse using built-in wireless load balancing. They share available power automatically, avoiding the need for separate circuits. Adding the Easee Equalizer enables dynamic load balancing across the whole property.

### Does the Easee One work with solar panels?

Yes, but you'll need the Easee Equalizer accessory (approximately £224 plus installation). Once fitted, you get two modes: Solar Only (charges exclusively from excess solar) and Grid + Solar (prioritises solar but supplements from the grid). If built-in solar integration is important, the [myenergi Zappi](/reviews/zappi-v2-review/) handles it natively.

### Is the 4G connectivity really free for life?

At the time of writing, yes — the integrated eSIM comes with a lifetime 4G subscription at no extra cost. Easee hasn't guaranteed this won't change in future, but Wi-Fi 2.4GHz is also supported as a backup, so you'd never be without connectivity.

### Do I need an earth rod for the Easee One?

No. The Easee One includes integrated open PEN conductor protection (compliant with BS 7671:2018 A1), so no separate earth rod is needed. This simplifies installation and keeps things tidier.

